text: This trailer really made me think about things. They made me think of a childhood memory. A memory which begins with me sitting in the corner of an alley in my hometown. I remember I looked out onto the street. I saw people walking. They were walking in an odd manner. A manner which deeply bothered me. It got to me on a psychological level. It was intense. It was full of life. It was everything I was missing. It was the essence of who we are as beings. It was a rhythmic series of movements set to a beat. A beat from a song. This movement was dance. Strange and beautiful. I never forgot. And from that day forward I decided to bring a little of that strange and beautiful to my YouTube channel. Not necessarily the dance component, but that same something that that dance made me feel. That joy. That life. And so, please check it out if you can.

text: just based on the cast it should have been easy to predict this wouldn't be a blockbuster, but i wouldn't have thought it would do *that* poorly. based on the trailers, the characters come off as contrived and entirely too jokey, imo.   too bad, too, because it seems like a fast and fun flick that, again imo, seems a bit overly produced, jokey, which is okay but better would be to have it be character-based humour, suffers from bad casting, failed to use their VOD option, and hit the theatres at the wrong time, not to mention the first trailer (as i recall) being a mess.  if there's a bright side here it's that this wasn't a terribly expensive movie to make, and in the end it'll probably break even eventually after what it can squeeze out of the box office, VOD, sales and rentals. it won't have 'legs,' but might find a cult following.   as far as max landis complaining about it being a flop and that there's no room for new movies not being a sequel, reboot, based on an established IP,  or a remake, that's just sour grapes, if you ask me. of course it's harder for original movies to draw in the crowds, but it's far from impossible, but you can't throw in some known actors that still work for relatively cheap and come off as a super-slick corporate product trying to be cool and expect great things.
